{ Blocking the way and supporting the pawn with the king.
Let us now look at Position 1.3. The black king has clearly reached the square. Now the pawn can promote only with the aid of the king. The easiest way is by blocking the enemy king's way.

This concept of blocking appears very often in pawn endings, but also in many others, and it is at the core of Rook vs. Pawn endings.

We can now state the second rule, which works with almost all pawns, the exception being the rook's pawn.
When possible, the stronger side's king will prevent its rival from standing in front of the pawn. If he succeeds, the pawn promotes. } { [%csl Gc6][%cal Gc6c7] }
1. Kc7 { Preventing ...Kc8 followed by ...Kb8 to stand in the pawn's way. Besides, from this square the king secures the pawn's path to b8. } { [%csl Gb2][%cal Gb3b4,Gb4b5,Gb5b6,Gb6b7,Gb7b8,Gb2b4] } 1... Ke6 { Since the black king cannot get in front of the pawn, he tries to attack the pawn before it reaches the secure zone (b6-b7-b8) .
Let us use this example to point out that, if the stronger side's king has secured the side opposition on the 7th rank, the defender will not be able to disturb the pawn. } { [%csl Rb6,Rb7,Rb8,Gb2][%cal Gb2b4] } 2. b4 Kd5 { [%csl Gb4][%cal Gb4b5] } 3. b5 { 1 -- 0 } { [%csl Bb5][%cal Bb5b6,Bb5b8,Bb5b7] } *


