{ #Key squares when the pawn has not reached the 5th rank.

"If the pawn has not reached the 5th rank, its key squares are two ranks ahead."

For example, for a pawn on the 4th rank, the key squares are on the 6th rank; in the diagram, c6, d6 and e6. But the rule still applies: if the white king occupies one, the pawn promotes. The key squares for a pawn on the 5th rank are the same as on the 4th rank. For a pawn on the 2nd or 3rd rank that rule (the key squares are two ranks ahead) is still valid. That is, for a d3 pawn, the key squares would be e5, d5 and c5; for a d2 pawn, e4, d4 and c4.

In the diagram position, the white king easily reaches one of the key squares, but sometimes opposition plays a role, causing the fight for the squares to be harder.
